<paper id="1551643125"><title>Measuring Expressiveness in Conceptual Modeling</title><year>2004</year><authors><author org="Otto‐von‐Guericke University of Magdeburg" id="79990569">Susanne Patig</author></authors><n_citation>10</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>118587617</reference><reference>1502040550</reference><reference>1520488951</reference><reference>1527321413</reference><reference>1537772377</reference><reference>1565722675</reference><reference>1592737338</reference><reference>1936689714</reference><reference>1982818491</reference><reference>1998044200</reference><reference>2000288666</reference><reference>2038650947</reference><reference>2045784797</reference><reference>2062844155</reference><reference>2078625208</reference><reference>2086980839</reference><reference>2105486835</reference><reference>2113827629</reference><reference>2132610455</reference><reference>2138073201</reference><reference>2180847728</reference></references><venue id="1134069326" type="C">Conference on Advanced Information Systems Engineering</venue><doi>10.1007/978-3-540-25975-6_11</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.48717">Information system</keyword><keyword weight="0.46834">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.44024">Systems engineering</keyword><keyword weight="0.54088">Conceptual model</keyword><keyword weight="0.45925">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.60447">Modeling language</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Artificial intelligence</keyword><keyword weight="0.45672">Natural language processing</keyword><keyword weight="0.44948">Schema (psychology)</keyword><keyword weight="0.52386">Software development</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Expressivity</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Expressiveness refers to things said in a description or sayable in a description language. It contributes to the quality of conceptual schemas and justifies the development of new modeling languages. Different notions of expressiveness exist, originating from different fields of computer science. In this paper, a framework is developed that defines different types of expressiveness, integrating the other notions. The framework contains a cardinal measure to assess the expressiveness of both descriptions and description languages.</abstract></paper>